initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories: "I'm feeling a mix of emotions, to be honest," Olly revealed, "I'm excited to be representing the UK on such a massive stage, but there's also a lot of pressure to do my country proud. I've been rehearsing non-stop to make sure my performance is perfect, and I'm feeling confident about my song, Dizzy. It's a high-energy track that I think will get the crowd on their feet." Olly took a deep breath, "But it's not just about the performance, it's about the whole experience. I'm looking forward to meeting the other contestants and learning about their cultures. It's going to be an incredible night, and I feel honored to be a part of it."

"As I walked into the venue for the first time, I was blown away by the sheer scale of it all," Olly continued, "the stage is enormous, and the lighting and sound systems are top-notch. I've been trying to take it all in, but it's hard not to feel a little overwhelmed. The other contestants seem really nice, though - we've all been chatting and sharing stories about our journeys to get here. There's a real sense of camaraderie, which is lovely. I've got my fingers crossed that we'll all be able to relax and enjoy the show tonight, despite the nerves. It's going to be a night to remember, that's for sure."

"As I made my way to my dressing room, I couldn't help but notice the rows of costumes and props lining the walls, each one meticulously labeled and organized. I felt a surge of excitement as I spotted my own name on one of the labels, and I couldn't wait to get into character and take the stage. My dresser, a lovely woman named Sarah, greeted me with a warm smile and helped me into my outfit. As I looked in the mirror, I barely recognized the person staring back at me - the transformation was incredible. I took a deep breath, trying to calm my nerves, and reminded myself that I'd rehearsed this a thousand times. But as I made my way to the wings, I couldn't shake the feeling that tonight was going to be something special."

"The orchestra was already seated, the musicians' instruments at the ready, and the conductor stood poised, baton in hand. I could feel the energy of the audience, their anticipation palpable as they waited for the curtain to rise. I took my place beside my fellow actors, our eyes locked on the stage manager as he gave us the final cue. The lights dimmed, the music swelled, and we were off, swept up in a whirlwind of drama and music that would carry us through the next two hours. I lost myself in the role, the words and movements flowing from me like second nature, as I gave myself over to the magic of the performance."

"As the first act drew to a close, I felt a rush of exhilaration, the applause of the audience like a wave crashing over me. Backstage, the air was electric with excitement, the cast and crew buzzing with energy as we prepared for the next act. I caught a glimpse of myself in the mirror, my character's makeup and costume transforming me into someone else entirely. I felt a thrill of pride and accomplishment, knowing that I had truly become someone else on that stage. The stage manager's voice called out the five-minute warning, and I took a deep breath, ready to dive back into the world of the play, to lose myself once again in the magic of the performance."

"As I waited in the wings, I could feel the anticipation building inside me, my heart pounding in time with the music that was about to swell. The lights dimmed, the orchestra began to play, and I stepped out onto the stage, the bright lights blinding me for a moment. The audience was a dark, formless mass, but I could sense their presence, their energy, their expectation. I took my place beside my fellow actors, and together we launched into the second act, the words and movements flowing from us like a well-rehearsed dance. The world of the play enveloped me once again, and I was no longer myself, but a character, a persona, a creation of my own imagination."

"As I spoke the words, I felt the character's emotions rising up inside me, her fears and desires, her triumphs and failures. The audience was entranced, hanging on every phrase, every gesture, and I could feel their emotions resonating with mine. The scene shifted, the lights changing to signal a new location, and I moved seamlessly into the next moment, the next emotional landscape. My fellow actors were extensions of myself, our bodies moving in tandem, our voices blending in harmony. We were a single entity, a living, breathing creature, and the audience was our heartbeat. I lost myself in the performance, forgot about the wings, the lights, the critics, and simply was. And in that moment, I knew I was exactly where I was meant to be."

"The applause was thunderous, a wave that crashed over me, but I didn't hear it. I was still lost in the world of the play, still feeling the character's pulse beating in time with mine. It was only when my fellow actors grasped my hands, their faces shining with tears and smiles, that I began to return to reality. The curtain call was a blur, a kaleidoscope of colors and applause, but what stood out was the sense of pride and accomplishment that swelled in my chest. I had given myself over to the performance, and it had given me everything in return. As I took my final bow, I felt the rush of adrenaline begin to ebb, replaced by a sense of peace, of knowing that I had found my true calling. The spotlight faded, and I walked offstage, into the warm darkness, ready to do it all again."

The dressing room was a flurry of activity, with actors and crew members congratulating me on my performance, but I barely registered their words. I was still basking in the glow of the show, reliving every moment, every line, every gesture. My costume was soaked with sweat, my makeup smeared, but I felt like I was walking on air. I changed quickly, my hands shaking with excitement as I peeled off my wig and prosthetics. As I emerged from the dressing room, I was met with a sea of familiar faces, all beaming with pride. My family, my friends, my agent - they were all there, waiting to congratulate me on my triumph. But one face stood out, one face that made my heart skip a beat. It was his, the director's, his eyes shining with a mixture of pride and admiration. He grasped my hand, his grip firm, and pulled me close. "You were born to do this," he whispered, his voice husky with emotion. And in that moment, I knew that I had found not only my true calling, but also my tribe, my family, my home.

As he released my hand, I felt a sense of belonging that I had never experienced before. The director's words echoed in my mind, and I knew that I had finally found my place in the world. I smiled, feeling a sense of gratitude towards this man who had given me the opportunity to shine. He smiled back, his eyes crinkling at the corners, and I felt a flutter in my chest. I turned to my family and friends, who were all waiting to congratulate me, but my gaze kept drifting back to the director. My agent, ever the opportunist, was already talking to him, discussing future projects and collaborations. I tuned them out, lost in my own little world of happiness. Suddenly, the director excused himself and took my hand again, leading me outside into the cool night air. The city lights twinkled around us, and I felt like I was on top of the world. "I have something to show you," he said, his voice low and mysterious. I nodded, my heart racing with anticipation, as he led me to a waiting car. We drove through the city, the wind blowing through my hair, until we reached a small, intimate restaurant on the outskirts of town. The sign above the door read "Private Party," and I knew that this was going to be a night to remember.

As we stepped inside, the maître d' greeted the director by name and led us to a cozy table by the window. The room was dimly lit, with soft music playing in the background, and the atmosphere was electric with an air of exclusivity. The director pulled out my chair and I sat down, feeling like royalty. He took the seat across from me, his eyes never leaving mine, and I felt a shiver run down my spine. "I wanted to celebrate your success in a more personal way," he said, his voice low and husky. "You deserve it." I blushed, feeling a sense of wonder at the thought of this powerful man going to so much trouble for me. The waiter appeared, pouring us each a glass of champagne, and the director raised his glass in a toast. "To you, my star," he said, his eyes sparkling with admiration. I echoed the toast, feeling like I was walking on clouds. As we sipped our champagne, I couldn't help but wonder what the rest of the night had in store for us.

The director leaned in, his face inches from mine, and I could feel the heat of his breath on my skin. "I have a few surprises planned for you tonight," he whispered, his voice sending shivers down my spine. "But first, let's order dinner. What do you say to the filet mignon?" I nodded, still feeling a little starstruck, and he gave the order to the waiter. As we waited for our food to arrive, we chatted about the film, and I was amazed at how down-to-earth and kind he was, despite his powerful status in the industry. He was charming and witty, and I found myself laughing and feeling more and more at ease in his presence. But beneath the surface, I couldn't shake the feeling that there was something more to this night, something that went beyond a simple celebration of my success.

As we sipped our wine and savored the exquisite flavors of the filet mignon, the conversation flowed effortlessly, and I found myself opening up to him in ways I never thought possible. He asked me about my childhood, my inspirations, and my dreams, and I felt like he was genuinely interested in getting to know me beyond the actress I had become. But every so often, I would catch him gazing at me with an intensity that made my heart skip a beat, and I couldn't help but wonder what lay behind those piercing eyes. As the main course came to a close, he pushed his chair back and smiled, his eyes crinkling at the corners. "Now, my dear, it's time for the first surprise of the evening," he said, his voice low and mysterious. "Are you ready?"

I nodded, my curiosity piqued, as he stood up and walked over to a nearby door that I hadn't noticed before. He produced a small key from his pocket and unlocked the door, revealing a dimly lit room with a grand piano at its center. The room was intimate, with candles flickering on the walls, and the air was thick with the scent of fresh flowers. "Welcome to my music room," he said, his eyes sparkling with excitement. As I took a seat on the velvet-covered stool he offered me, he began to play a haunting melody that sent shivers down my spine. I nodded, my throat dry, as he reached out a hand and gently brushed a strand of hair behind my ear.
